# Screen Mirror VR – Architecture

## Stack

- **Application**: Web app (PWA). One codebase; runs in browser on PC (sender) and mobile (receiver). Prioritize Windows; must also work on Linux.
- **Capture (PC)**: `getDisplayMedia()` (Screen Capture API). No native desktop app required.
- **Transport**: WebRTC (RTCPeerConnection). Video/audio sent P2P for low latency.
- **Signaling**: WebSocket server (Node.js or similar) **always run locally** by the user (e.g. `npm start`). Only for SDP/ICE exchange; no media through server. Do not introduce any dependency on remote backends or hosted services so that any user can run the app locally without depending on third parties.
- **Connectivity**: Wireless (WiFi) and wired (USB tethering). Same WebRTC flow; "wired" = phone gets IP via tethering, then same URL.

## Roles

- **Sender**: Browser on Windows/Linux PC. Captures screen via `getDisplayMedia()`, creates offer, sends stream over WebRTC.
- **Receiver**: Browser (or PWA) on mobile. Receives stream, displays with configurable view mode (normal / SBS for VR).

## View Modes (receiver only)

- **Normal**: Single full-screen video.
- **VR (SBS)**: Same frame drawn twice (left half / right half) for cardboard-style VR; optional Top-Bottom. No second stream; single stream, duplicated in layout.

## Constraints

- **No remote server**: The app must run entirely from a local process. Any user can clone, install, and run without depending on external services. STUN/TURN may be configured by the user (e.g. env) but must not be required by default.
- Test on Windows first; ensure Linux (Chrome/Firefox) works.
- Do not depend on OS-specific APIs for capture; use only web APIs.
- Prefer HTTPS or localhost for `getDisplayMedia()`; document any TLS requirements.
